  <span>ğŸ§„ Ginger-garlic</span>
  <span>âœ¨ Garam masala</span>
</div>

<div class="page">

  <div class="frozen-box">
    <h3>A note on big, frozen pieces</h3>
    <p>Thick bone-in pieces with skin and fat are actually ideal for a curry like this â€” the fat renders slowly into the gravy giving it body and depth, and the bones release gelatin that thickens everything naturally. The one thing to do right: <strong>thaw completely before cooking</strong>, then pat dry. Surface moisture is the enemy of a good sear and will steam the chicken instead of browning it.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- INGREDIENTS -->
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-num">01</span>
    <h2>What You'll Need</h2>
    <div class="deco-line"></div>
  </div>

  <div class="ing-group">
    <div class="ing-group-title">ğŸ” The chicken</div>
    <div class="ingredients-grid">
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">~2.5 lbs</span><span class="ing-name">bone-in chicken pieces <span class="ing-note">skin-on, fully thawed, patted dry</span></span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">1 tsp</span><span class="ing-name">salt</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">Â½ tsp</span><span class="ing-name">turmeric</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">1 tsp</span><span class="ing-name">red chili powder</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="ing-group">
    <div class="ing-group-title">ğŸ«• The base</div>
    <div class="ingredients-grid">
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">3 tbsp</span><span class="ing-name">mustard oil <span class="ing-note">or any neutral oil</span></span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">2â€“3</span><span class="ing-name">bay leaves</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">4</span><span class="ing-name">green cardamom pods <span class="ing-note">lightly crushed</span></span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">4</span><span class="ing-name">cloves</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">1 stick</span><span class="ing-name">cinnamon</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">1 tsp</span><span class="ing-name">cumin seeds</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">2 medium</span><span class="ing-name">onions <span class="ing-note">finely sliced</span></span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">1Â½ tbsp</span><span class="ing-name">ginger-garlic paste</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">2 medium</span><span class="ing-name">tomatoes <span class="ing-note">roughly chopped</span></span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">3â€“5</span><span class="ing-name">green chilies <span class="ing-note">slit lengthwise</span></span></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="ing-group">
    <div class="ing-group-title">ğŸŒ¶ Ground spices</div>
    <div class="ingredients-grid">
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">Â½ tsp</span><span class="ing-name">turmeric</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">1Â½ tsp</span><span class="ing-name">red chili powder <span class="ing-note">adjust to heat preference</span></span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">1Â½ tsp</span><span class="ing-name">coriander powder</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">1 tsp</span><span class="ing-name">cumin powder</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">to taste</span><span class="ing-name">salt</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">1â€“1.5 cups</span><span class="ing-name">water</span></div>
      <div class="ingredient"><span class="ing-amount">Â½ tsp</span><span class="ing-name">garam masala <span class="ing-note">to finish</span></span></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="flavor-banner">
    <h3>Why this works with fatty pieces</h3>
    <p>Most recipes ask you to trim the fat. Don't. As the chicken slow-cooks, the fat under the skin liquefies and bleeds into the masala, enriching it in a way that lean breast meat simply can't. The tomato provides enough acidity to cut through the richness, and the green chilies â€” added early â€” mellow into the gravy rather than sit on top of it. This is a curry that improves dramatically if you let it rest 15â€“20 minutes before serving.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- METHOD -->
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-num">02</span>
    <h2>How to Make It</h2>
    <div class="deco-line"></div>
  </div>

  <div class="steps">

    <div class="step">
      <span class="step-icon">ğŸ§Š</span>
      <div class="step-num">1</div>
      <div class="step-title">Thaw & prep</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Thaw chicken completely â€” ideally overnight in the fridge, or in cold water for a few hours.</li>
        <li>Pat every piece completely dry with kitchen paper. This is not optional.</li>
        <li>Rub with salt, turmeric, and red chili powder. Set aside while you prep everything else.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="warning-note">Wet chicken won't brown â€” it steams. Dry it thoroughly, even if it takes a few paper towels.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <span class="step-icon">ğŸ”¥</span>
      <div class="step-num">2</div>
      <div class="step-title">Render & sear</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Heat oil in a heavy-bottomed pot or kadai on medium-high. If using mustard oil, smoke it first then reduce.</li>
        <li>Add chicken skin-side down. Don't touch it for 3â€“4 minutes â€” let it sear properly.</li>
        <li>Flip; sear the other side 2â€“3 min. The skin should be golden, not grey.</li>
        <li>Remove and set aside. The rendered fat stays in the pot â€” that's flavour.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="tip-note">Work in batches if needed. Crowding the pan drops the temperature and you'll get steaming, not searing.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <span class="step-icon">ğŸ§…</span>
      <div class="step-num">3</div>
      <div class="step-title">Build the masala</div>
      <ul>
        <li>In the same pot, reduce to medium. Add whole spices â€” bay leaves, cardamom, cloves, cinnamon, cumin seeds. Let them sizzle 30 seconds.</li>
        <li>Add sliced onions. Fry slowly until deep golden brown â€” 15â€“20 minutes. Don't rush this; it's the backbone of the gravy.</li>
        <li>Add ginger-garlic paste; fry until the raw smell is gone, 2 min.</li>
        <li>Add slit green chilies now â€” early addition mellows their heat into the base.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <span class="step-icon">ğŸ…</span>
      <div class="step-num">4</div>
      <div class="step-title">Tomato & spices</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Add chopped tomatoes. Cook on medium, stirring occasionally, until completely broken down and the oil separates â€” about 10 minutes.</li>
        <li>Add all ground spices: turmeric, chili powder, coriander, cumin, salt.</li>
        <li>Stir and cook 2â€“3 minutes until the masala is deep in colour and fragrant.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="tip-note">The masala is ready when you see oil pooling at the edges and the mix looks almost paste-like. Don't add the chicken before this point.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <span class="step-icon">ğŸ—</span>
      <div class="step-num">5</div>
      <div class="step-title">Return the chicken</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Add the seared chicken back into the pot. Turn to coat every piece in the masala.</li>
        <li>Cook on medium heat without water for 5â€“7 minutes â€” let the chicken absorb the masala.</li>
        <li>Add 1â€“1.5 cups warm water. Stir, scraping up anything stuck on the bottom.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="step full">
      <span class="step-icon">â³</span>
      <div class="step-num">6</div>
      <div class="step-title">Low & slow to the finish</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Bring to a gentle boil, then reduce to low. Cover and cook 30â€“40 minutes for big bone-in pieces â€” thick thighs and drumsticks need time.</li>
        <li>Check every 10â€“15 min; stir gently, add a splash of water if it's catching.</li>
        <li>The chicken is done when the meat pulls back from the bone and the gravy is thick and glossy.</li>
        <li>Sprinkle garam masala, cover, and rest off the heat for 15â€“20 minutes before serving. The flavour deepens noticeably in this rest.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

  </div>

  <div class="tips-row">
    <div class="tip"><strong>On the fat & skin</strong> Leave it on during cooking â€” it bastes the meat from inside and enriches the gravy. If you find it too rich after cooking, you can skim excess oil from the surface before serving.</div>
    <div class="tip"><strong>On the onions</strong> The 15â€“20 minute onion fry feels long but it's non-negotiable for this style of curry. Under-fried onions give a raw, sharp flavour; deeply golden onions dissolve into a sweet, complex base.</div>
    <div class="tip"><strong>On the rest</strong> This curry is noticeably better after 15â€“20 minutes off the heat. Even better the next day â€” the spices settle, the fat redistributes, and the whole thing deepens.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="serve">
    <h3>Serve alongside</h3>
    <div class="serve-options">
      <span class="serve-pill">ğŸš Steamed rice</span>
      <span class="serve-pill">ğŸ«“ Roti or paratha</span>
      <span class="serve-pill">ğŸ§… Raw sliced onion & lemon</span>
      <span class="serve-pill">ğŸ«™ Pickle</span>
    </div>
  </div>

